title: For Sale:  a 28 inch octagon barrel.
postcontent: The bore appears to be perfect as there is no sign of pits or rust – very shiny. Sights are buckhorn rear and standard blade on the front. The stock shows minimal wear with only small nicks and dings that one might expect on a gun this old - but no major dents and the metal to wood fit is very tight. There is a slight crack where the stock meets the butt plate but it took me years before I even noticed this. This is an ANTIQUE, NO FFL is require.This is the High Wall model –where you cannot see the hammer with the falling block down. The gun would become known as the Model 1885 although the model name had not appeared on the gun when production ceased in 1920. In 2005 Winchester reintroduced this gun and I think the model name does appear on these guns. This gun used case hardening steel and Winchester would not start bluing these guns until 1906, used (128 year old) Winchester Model 1885 High Wall 38WFC with a 28 inch octagon barrel - number 1 barrel weight stamped just in front of forearm. This gun was invented by John Moses Browning when he was just 23 years old and he was awarded a patient on Oct 7, 1879 (see picture 7) as the patent data.. The 38WCF is sort of misleading as this was the old 38-40 cartridge and even this is misleading as you would think it is a 38 caliber but it is a 40 caliber and the 38 is the amount of black powder. Ammo is easy to find as this is a common and popular “Cowboy” shooting cartridge. Shipping and insurance will be buyer’s responsibility and will be notified of exact amount before making payment. No packing, handling or other cost added. Must be paid in Money Order or Certified Check.

title: For Sale:  Norwegian Krag Jorgensen
postcontent: One very nice Norwegian Krag Jorgensen in 6.5x55mm Swedish.  This particular rifle was manufactured in 1914.  This rifle has been sporterized by a previous owner, but the job appears to be very well done.  The serial numbers of all the components match.  The military rear sight has been removed and there has been a Lyman peep sight installed on the rear of the reciever, as well as a higher front sight blade.  If you have any questions please do not hesitate to ask.       I purchased a Lee handloader in the 6.5x55mm Swedish caliber to load for this rifle and I am throwing that in with it.  Much of what I researched online said that modern 6.5x55mm Swedish was too hot for these Norwegian Krag Jorgensens so handloading was recommended.  I also read that US manufactured ammo in 6.5x55mm Swedish is loaded to lower pressures so that it can be shot in Norwegian Krags.  Being the cautious individual that I am, I have only fired handloads in this rifle.        My schedule is pretty full so I must insist that this sale is local pick up only.
